title.narrative: OUTPUT 5.2 ADOLESCENT ENGAGEMENT ON CHILD PROTECTION

description.narrative: Output 2 (Adolescent engagement on child protection): Girls and boys including children with disabilities have strengthened capacity including digital literacy and safety, and opportunities to develop, access and utilize information for enhanced protection from violence, exploitation and child marriage., which contributes to Prevention Of Harmful Practice, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Communications, Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Girls and boys are progressively empowered and protected from violence, exploitation, neglect and harmful practices by functioning, quality child protection systems and positive social norms at national and subnational level including in humanitarian settings.

description.narrative: Underpinning all efforts to prevent and respond to all forms of VAC in Indonesia was the deliberate engagement of children and adolescents in all aspects of the child protection programme. The Ministry of Education, Culture, Research and Technology (MOECRT) embraced new initiatives and successfully scaled up ROOTS, an adolescent-driven school-based bullying prevention model support by UNICEF. Importantly, the Children’s Forum, including representatives of children with disabilities, were at the forefront of developing guidelines, known as 2P (Pelopor dan Pelapor or ‘Pioneers and Reporters’), which aim to strengthen children’s capacities to advocate and report on VAC and other protection issues.; | Status:Met | As-of Date:30/11/2021
